## App-managed Companion Layout

### Context

In `managed_synced` mode the Postgres layout per graph version consists of three
objects: a `*_sync` table (owned by Lakeflow), a `*__app` companion (writable by
the app for reasoning / materialise), and a union view that readers query.
In `app_managed` mode only a single flat table existed, which meant materialise
writes were mixed with warehouse data and no clean separation was possible between
bulk-loaded triples and app-generated triples.

This change makes `app_managed` use the same 3-object layout.  The app streams
warehouse data into `*_sync` (instead of Lakeflow), the companion absorbs
reasoning output, and the union view provides a unified read surface.

### Changes

1. `src/back/core/graphdb/lakebase/_companion_ddl.py`
   - Added `ensure_synced(cur, schema, synced)` — creates the `*_sync` bulk-data
     table with indexes (used by the `app_managed` build path).
   - Added `drop_synced(cur, synced)` — drops the `*_sync` table.
   - Updated module docstring to document that both modes share the 3-object layout.

2. `src/back/core/graphdb/lakebase/LakebaseFlatStore.py`
   - `create_table()` — now creates `*_sync` + `*__app` + union view in
     `app_managed` mode (was a single flat table); `managed_synced` remains a
     no-op deferred to `SyncedTableManager`.
   - `drop_table()` — drops all 3 Postgres objects for `app_managed` (no Lakeflow
     API call); `managed_synced` branch unchanged.
   - `_writable_table_id()` — returns `companion_phy(name)` for both modes so
     reasoning / materialise always target `*__app`.
   - `optimize_table()` — vacuums `*_sync` and `*__app` for `app_managed`;
     vacuums companion only for `managed_synced`.
   - Extracted `_copy_insert_batch_phy(phy, batch)` private helper (takes the
     physical table name directly); `_copy_insert_batch` delegates to it.
   - Added `bulk_load_into_sync(table_name, iterator, *, batch_size, on_progress)`
     — public method for the build pipeline; writes to `*_sync` via
     `_copy_insert_batch_phy`.

3. `src/back/objects/digitaltwin/_build_pipeline.py`
   - `_apply_full_rebuild()` — when the store exposes `bulk_load_into_sync`,
     warehouse data is routed there (targeting `*_sync`); non-Lakebase backends
     fall back to the legacy `_stream_triples_into_store` path.

4. `tests/test_lakebase_flat_store.py`
   - Updated `test_create_table_issues_schema_ddl_and_indexes` for the new 3-object DDL.
   - Added `test_writable_table_id_is_companion_for_app_managed`.
   - Added `test_drop_table_app_managed_drops_view_companion_and_sync`.
   - Added `test_optimize_table_vacuums_sync_and_companion_for_app_managed`.
   - Added `test_bulk_load_into_sync_writes_to_sync_table`.

5. `tests/test_build_pipeline_streaming.py`
   - Updated `TestFullRebuildProgressMessage._full_pipe` to mock
     `store.bulk_load_into_sync` (new code path) instead of
     `_stream_triples_into_store`.

### Modified files

- `src/back/core/graphdb/lakebase/_companion_ddl.py`
- `src/back/core/graphdb/lakebase/LakebaseFlatStore.py`
- `src/back/objects/digitaltwin/_build_pipeline.py`
- `tests/test_lakebase_flat_store.py`
- `tests/test_build_pipeline_streaming.py`

### Test result

1979 passed, 80 skipped — all tests green.

